Note:
==============================================================================
FALCON-FFT : complex Float64 FFT over the cyclotomic ring Z[X]/(X^n + 1)
==============================================================================

Per the Falcon NIST PQC submission (keygen.c falcon.c), the lattice basis
generator and the Fast Fourier Sampler operate in the FFT domain of the
2*n-th cyclotomic root structure. The forward FFT maps a real polynomial
of degree n-1 over Z[X]/(X^n + 1) into a length-n array of complex numbers
whose entries are the polynomial evaluated at the primitive 2*n-th roots of
unity zeta_k = exp(i * (2k+1) * pi / n) for k = 0..n-1.

Equivalent formulation (radix-2 Cooley-Tukey, DIT):
  A polynomial f(X) of degree < n in Z[X]/(X^n + 1) is represented as a
  flat array of n complex numbers a[k] = f(zeta_{2k+1}) for k = 0..n-1
  where zeta_j = exp(i * j * pi / n) is a primitive 2*n-th root of unity.

Storage layout:
  An FFT-domain polynomial occupies 16*n bytes of arena memory. Each pair
  of 8-byte Float64 values (real, imaginary) is stored at offset 16*k
  and 16*k + 8 respectively, indexed by k = 0..n-1.

A polynomial in coefficient form (input to fft_forward) likewise occupies
16*n bytes: the real part of the k-th coefficient at offset 16*k, the
imaginary part (zero for real input) at offset 16*k + 8.

Operations provided:
  - fft_forward         : in-place forward FFT
  - fft_inverse         : in-place inverse FFT (with 1/n scaling)
  - fft_mul_pointwise   : c[k] = a[k] * b[k]
  - fft_add_pointwise   : c[k] = a[k] + b[k]
  - fft_sub_pointwise   : c[k] = a[k] - b[k]
  - fft_conj_pointwise  : c[k] = conj(a[k])
  - fft_load_from_int_poly  : real coefs read from int16 array
  - fft_load_from_int_poly_signed : signed integer coefs (Falcon f, g)
  - fft_extract_real_round  : write real-part-rounded ints back

This module depends on falcon_fp.runa for hardware Float64 arithmetic.

Cost analysis for Falcon-512 (n=512):
  - Forward FFT: log2(512) = 9 passes, each pass 256 butterflies. Each
    butterfly is 6 fp_add/fp_sub + 4 fp_mul (complex mul). Total:
    9 * 256 * (6 + 4) = 23040 SSE2 ops, plus 256 twiddle factor lookups
    via fp_cos and fp_sin.
  - Inverse FFT: same complexity plus a final n-scaling pass.
  - Pointwise mul: 256 complex multiplies (4 fp_mul + 2 fp_sub per coef).

Memory: one in-place FFT scratch = 16*n bytes = 8192 bytes for n=512.

Constant-time considerations:
  All butterfly indexing depends on the public parameter n; the only
  data-dependent operation is FP add/sub/mul which is approximately
  constant-time on modern x86_64. See falcon_fp.runa security notes for
  the denormal-assist and division-latency caveats.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/crypto/pq/falcon_fp.runa" as FP

Note:
==============================================================================
Helpers for storing complex Float64 pairs into arena buffers
==============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "fft_get_real" takes buf as Integer, idx as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Loads the real part of the idx-th complex coefficient.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the 8-byte value at offset 16*idx.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single 64-bit load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pointer must be 8-aligned arena memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let off be idx multiplied by 16
    Return Memory.memory_get_int64(buf, off)
End Process

Process called "fft_get_imag" takes buf as Integer, idx as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Loads the imaginary part of the idx-th complex coefficient.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Returns the 8-byte value at offset 16*idx + 8.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single 64-bit load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pointer must be 8-aligned arena memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let off be idx multiplied by 16
    Set off to off plus 8
    Return Memory.memory_get_int64(buf, off)
End Process

Process called "fft_set_real" takes buf as Integer, idx as Integer, value as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stores the real part of the idx-th complex coefficient.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Writes the 8-byte value at offset 16*idx.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single 64-bit store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pointer must be writable arena memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let off be idx multiplied by 16
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, off, value)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_set_imag" takes buf as Integer, idx as Integer, value as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stores the imaginary part of the idx-th complex coefficient.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Writes the 8-byte value at offset 16*idx + 8.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single 64-bit store.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pointer must be writable arena memory.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let off be idx multiplied by 16
    Set off to off plus 8
    Memory.memory_set_int64(buf, off, value)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_zero" takes buf as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Zero an n-coefficient FFT buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Sets 16*n bytes to zero via Memory.memory_zero.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Linear in n.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public sizes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let bytes be n multiplied by 16
    Memory.memory_zero(buf, bytes)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_copy" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Copy an n-coefficient FFT buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Copies 16*n bytes via Memory.memory_copy.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Linear in n.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller-managed alignment.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let bytes be n multiplied by 16
    Memory.memory_copy(dest, src, bytes)
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
TWIDDLE FACTOR COMPUTATION
==============================================================================
For Z[X]/(X^n + 1) the FFT evaluation points are the primitive 2n-th roots
of unity at odd positions: zeta_k = exp(i * (2k+1) * pi / n) for k = 0..n-1.
:End Note

Process called "fft_twiddle" takes k as Integer, n as Integer, result_real_ptr as Integer, result_imag_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes zeta_k = exp(i * (2k+1) * pi / n) and writes its real and
    imaginary parts to the two pointer locations.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Argument theta = (2k+1) * pi / n. Real part = cos(theta), imag = sin(theta).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) with constant transcendental cost (~150 cycles per call).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public twiddle index.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let two_k_plus_1 be 2 multiplied by k plus 1
    Let two_k_plus_1_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with two_k_plus_1
    Let n_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with n
    Let pi_v be proc FP.fp_pi
    Let prod1 be proc FP.fp_mul with two_k_plus_1_f, pi_v
    Let theta be proc FP.fp_div with prod1, n_f
    Let cr be proc FP.fp_cos with theta
    Let ci be proc FP.fp_sin with theta
    Memory.memory_set_int64(result_real_ptr, 0, cr)
    Memory.memory_set_int64(result_imag_ptr, 0, ci)
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
COMPLEX MULTIPLY HELPER
==============================================================================
(a + bi)(c + di) = (ac - bd) + (ad + bc) i
:End Note

Process called "fft_complex_mul" takes a_real as Float, a_imag as Float, b_real as Float, b_imag as Float, out_real_ptr as Integer, out_imag_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Complex multiply.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Real part = a_real*b_real - a_imag*b_imag.
    Imag part = a_real*b_imag + a_imag*b_real.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    4 mulsd + 2 addsd/subsd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ar_br be proc FP.fp_mul with a_real, b_real
    Let ai_bi be proc FP.fp_mul with a_imag, b_imag
    Let real_out be proc FP.fp_sub with ar_br, ai_bi
    Let ar_bi be proc FP.fp_mul with a_real, b_imag
    Let ai_br be proc FP.fp_mul with a_imag, b_real
    Let imag_out be proc FP.fp_add with ar_bi, ai_br
    Memory.memory_set_int64(out_real_ptr, 0, real_out)
    Memory.memory_set_int64(out_imag_ptr, 0, imag_out)
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
FORWARD FFT
==============================================================================
Cooley-Tukey radix-2 DIT FFT for Z[X]/(X^n + 1).

For Z[X]/(X^n + 1), the structure differs slightly from the standard DFT.
Each "split" pass uses twiddles that are primitive 2n-th roots of unity
indexed by the bit-reversal of the current block position. We compute the
required twiddle at each butterfly site using fft_twiddle.

The pass structure: levels = log2(n). At level L (counting from 0 at the
top), the array is partitioned into 2^L blocks of size n/2^L. Each block
is butterflied with one twiddle, then halved by the next pass.
:End Note

Process called "fft_bit_reverse" takes value as Integer, width as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Bit-reverse an integer interpreted as a width-bit number.
    Used by fft_forward / fft_inverse to compute the correct twiddle
    indices at each FFT pass (the gm_tab in Pornin's reference embeds
    this bit-reverse into the precomputed table; we materialise it
    inline here).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Iteratively reads the low bit of value into the high end of result,
    width times.  Returns 0 when width is 0 (which is the case at the
    top-most FFT pass with m=1).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(width).  For Falcon-1024, width <= 9 inside fft_forward; the cost
    is dominated by the surrounding transcendentals anyway.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Public sizes only.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be 0
    Let v be value
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than width:
        Let bit be v bitwise_and 1
        Set result to result shifted left by 1
        Set result to result bitwise_or bit
        Set v to v shifted right by 1
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "fft_forward" takes arena as Integer, buf as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    In-place forward FFT for an n-coefficient cyclotomic Z[X]/(X^n+1) buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Cooley-Tukey DIT. At each level, walk the array in blocks of size m,
    applying the appropriate twiddle to each butterfly pair (a, b):
        a' = a + zeta * b
        b' = a - zeta * b
    The twiddle index for block index j at level with block size m must be
    computed so that the resulting transform matches evaluation at the
    primitive 2n-th odd roots of unity zeta_k = exp(i*(2k+1)*pi/n).

    Recursive factorisation of X^n+1:
      Pass 1 (m=1):
        X^n+1 = (X^(n/2) - i)(X^(n/2) + i)
        Single twiddle = i = exp(i*pi/2).
      Pass 2 (m=2):
        X^(n/2) - i = (X^(n/4) - omega_0)(X^(n/4) + omega_0)
                       where omega_0 = exp(i*pi/4) = sqrt(i)
        X^(n/2) + i = (X^(n/4) - omega_1)(X^(n/4) + omega_1)
                       where omega_1 = exp(i*3pi/4) = sqrt(-i)
        Twiddles: omega_0, omega_1 = exp(i*pi/4), exp(i*3pi/4).
      Pass u (m = 2^u):
        Twiddle for sub-block j is exp(i*(2*revbits_u(j)+1)*pi/(2*m))
        where revbits_u is bit-reversal over u bits.

    The bit-reversal is essential: Pornin's reference embeds it in the
    precomputed gm_tab, which has gm_tab[m+i] = (cos(theta), sin(theta))
    with theta = (2*revbits_u(i)+1)*pi/(2*m).  We materialise the
    bit-reversal inline via fft_bit_reverse.

    Implementation outline:
      hn = n / 2; t = hn; m = 1; u = 0
      Repeat while t > 0:
          For each j in 0..m-1:
              s_inner = revbits_u(j)
              theta = (2*s_inner + 1) * pi / (2*m)
              zeta = exp(i*theta)
              For each i in 0..t-1:
                  k = 2*j*t + i
                  a = buf[k]
                  b = zeta * buf[k+t]
                  buf[k]   = a + b
                  buf[k+t] = a - b
          m = m * 2; t = t / 2; u = u + 1
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(n log n) Float64 ops. Twiddle factors are recomputed on the fly via
    cos/sin; an optional cache could halve transcendental cost but is not
    used here.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Operates on public dimension n; only Float arithmetic on coefficients
    is data-dependent.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let hn be n shifted right by 1
    Let t be hn
    Let m be 1
    Let u be 0
    While t is greater than 0:
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than m:
            Note: Twiddle: zeta = exp(i*(2*revbits_u(j)+1)*pi/(2*m)).
            Note: At pass u (m=2^u sub-blocks), revbits over u bits is
            Note: required so the inner-loop ordering matches Pornin's
            Note: pre-computed bit-reversed gm_tab.
            Let s_inner be proc fft_bit_reverse with j, u
            Let s_eff be 2 multiplied by s_inner plus 1
            Let s_eff_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with s_eff
            Let m2 be m multiplied by 2
            Let m2_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with m2
            Let pi_v be proc FP.fp_pi
            Let prod1 be proc FP.fp_mul with s_eff_f, pi_v
            Let theta be proc FP.fp_div with prod1, m2_f
            Let zr be proc FP.fp_cos with theta
            Let zi be proc FP.fp_sin with theta

            Let i be 0
            While i is less than t:
                Let k be 2 multiplied by j multiplied by t plus i
                Let kp be k plus t
                Let ar be proc fft_get_real with buf, k
                Let ai be proc fft_get_imag with buf, k
                Let br_raw be proc fft_get_real with buf, kp
                Let bi_raw be proc fft_get_imag with buf, kp

                Note: b' = zeta * b = (zr*br_raw - zi*bi_raw) + (zr*bi_raw + zi*br_raw)i
                Let zr_br be proc FP.fp_mul with zr, br_raw
                Let zi_bi be proc FP.fp_mul with zi, bi_raw
                Let br be proc FP.fp_sub with zr_br, zi_bi
                Let zr_bi be proc FP.fp_mul with zr, bi_raw
                Let zi_br be proc FP.fp_mul with zi, br_raw
                Let bi be proc FP.fp_add with zr_bi, zi_br

                Let new_ar be proc FP.fp_add with ar, br
                Let new_ai be proc FP.fp_add with ai, bi
                Let new_br be proc FP.fp_sub with ar, br
                Let new_bi be proc FP.fp_sub with ai, bi

                proc fft_set_real with buf, k, new_ar
                proc fft_set_imag with buf, k, new_ai
                proc fft_set_real with buf, kp, new_br
                proc fft_set_imag with buf, kp, new_bi

                Set i to i plus 1
            End While

            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Set m to m multiplied by 2
        Set t to t shifted right by 1
        Set u to u plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
INVERSE FFT
==============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "fft_inverse" takes arena as Integer, buf as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    In-place inverse FFT.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Gentleman-Sande DIF inverse. Mirrors fft_forward with twiddle direction
    reversed (negated imaginary part) and an outer 1/n scaling pass.

    Loop structure (reverse of forward):
      m = n; t = 1
      Repeat while m > 1:
          For each j in 0..(m/2)-1:
              s_eff = (m/2) + j
              theta = s_eff * pi / m, twiddle = exp(-i*theta) = (cos, -sin)
              For each i in 0..t-1:
                  k = 2*j*t + i
                  a = buf[k]; b = buf[k+t]
                  buf[k]   = a + b
                  buf[k+t] = (a - b) * twiddle*
          m = m/2; t = t*2
      Final scaling: buf[k] = buf[k] * (1/n) for all k.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    O(n log n).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Operates on FFT-domain data.
    @End Security_Scope
    Note: Compute log2(hm) for each pass so we can bit-reverse j.
    Note: At each inverse pass with current m, the corresponding forward
    Note: pass used forward_m = hm = m/2 sub-blocks, with log2(hm) bits
    Note: of bit-reversal needed for the twiddle index.
    Let m be n
    Let t be 1
    Note: log2_hm starts at log2(n/2).
    Let log2_hm be 0
    Let tmp be n shifted right by 1
    While tmp is greater than 1:
        Set log2_hm to log2_hm plus 1
        Set tmp to tmp shifted right by 1
    End While
    While m is greater than 1:
        Let hm be m shifted right by 1
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than hm:
            Note: Twiddle index: s_inner = revbits_{log2(hm)}(j), then
            Note: theta = (2*s_inner + 1) * pi / m (matches forward pass
            Note: for that m; conjugation via negated sin gives the inverse).
            Let s_inner be proc fft_bit_reverse with j, log2_hm
            Let s_eff be 2 multiplied by s_inner plus 1
            Let s_eff_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with s_eff
            Let m_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with m
            Let pi_v be proc FP.fp_pi
            Let prod1 be proc FP.fp_mul with s_eff_f, pi_v
            Let theta be proc FP.fp_div with prod1, m_f
            Let zr be proc FP.fp_cos with theta
            Let zi_pos be proc FP.fp_sin with theta
            Let zi be proc FP.fp_neg with zi_pos

            Let i be 0
            While i is less than t:
                Let k be 2 multiplied by j multiplied by t plus i
                Let kp be k plus t
                Let ar be proc fft_get_real with buf, k
                Let ai be proc fft_get_imag with buf, k
                Let br be proc fft_get_real with buf, kp
                Let bi be proc fft_get_imag with buf, kp

                Let sum_r be proc FP.fp_add with ar, br
                Let sum_i be proc FP.fp_add with ai, bi
                Let dif_r be proc FP.fp_sub with ar, br
                Let dif_i be proc FP.fp_sub with ai, bi

                Note: (dif_r + dif_i i) * (zr + zi i)
                Let nr1 be proc FP.fp_mul with dif_r, zr
                Let ni1 be proc FP.fp_mul with dif_i, zi
                Let new_br be proc FP.fp_sub with nr1, ni1
                Let nr2 be proc FP.fp_mul with dif_r, zi
                Let ni2 be proc FP.fp_mul with dif_i, zr
                Let new_bi be proc FP.fp_add with nr2, ni2

                proc fft_set_real with buf, k, sum_r
                proc fft_set_imag with buf, k, sum_i
                proc fft_set_real with buf, kp, new_br
                proc fft_set_imag with buf, kp, new_bi

                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Set m to m shifted right by 1
        Set t to t multiplied by 2
        Set log2_hm to log2_hm minus 1
    End While

    Note: Final 1/n scaling
    Let one_v be proc FP.fp_one
    Let n_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with n
    Let inv_n be proc FP.fp_div with one_v, n_f
    Let k2 be 0
    While k2 is less than n:
        Let r be proc fft_get_real with buf, k2
        Let i_v be proc fft_get_imag with buf, k2
        Let nr be proc FP.fp_mul with r, inv_n
        Let ni be proc FP.fp_mul with i_v, inv_n
        proc fft_set_real with buf, k2, nr
        proc fft_set_imag with buf, k2, ni
        Set k2 to k2 plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
Pointwise operations in FFT domain
==============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "fft_mul_pointwise" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, c as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    c[k] = a[k] * b[k] across complex pairs.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loop over n coefficients, complex multiply each.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    n complex muls = 4*n mulsd + 2*n addsd/subsd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    FFT-domain data may be secret; operations are CT-friendly.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let ar be proc fft_get_real with a, k
        Let ai be proc fft_get_imag with a, k
        Let br be proc fft_get_real with b, k
        Let bi be proc fft_get_imag with b, k

        Let p1 be proc FP.fp_mul with ar, br
        Let p2 be proc FP.fp_mul with ai, bi
        Let new_r be proc FP.fp_sub with p1, p2
        Let p3 be proc FP.fp_mul with ar, bi
        Let p4 be proc FP.fp_mul with ai, br
        Let new_i be proc FP.fp_add with p3, p4

        proc fft_set_real with c, k, new_r
        proc fft_set_imag with c, k, new_i

        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_add_pointwise" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, c as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    c[k] = a[k] + b[k].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loop over real and imaginary parts.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    2*n addsd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    CT.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let ar be proc fft_get_real with a, k
        Let ai be proc fft_get_imag with a, k
        Let br be proc fft_get_real with b, k
        Let bi be proc fft_get_imag with b, k
        Let sum_r be proc FP.fp_add with ar, br
        Let sum_i be proc FP.fp_add with ai, bi
        proc fft_set_real with c, k, sum_r
        proc fft_set_imag with c, k, sum_i
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_sub_pointwise" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, c as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    c[k] = a[k] - b[k].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loop over real and imaginary parts.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    2*n subsd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    CT.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let ar be proc fft_get_real with a, k
        Let ai be proc fft_get_imag with a, k
        Let br be proc fft_get_real with b, k
        Let bi be proc fft_get_imag with b, k
        Let dif_r be proc FP.fp_sub with ar, br
        Let dif_i be proc FP.fp_sub with ai, bi
        proc fft_set_real with c, k, dif_r
        proc fft_set_imag with c, k, dif_i
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_conj" takes a as Integer, c as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    c[k] = conj(a[k]) = (real, -imag).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Loop over coefficients negating the imaginary part.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    n fp_neg.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    CT.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let ar be proc fft_get_real with a, k
        Let ai be proc fft_get_imag with a, k
        Let neg_ai be proc FP.fp_neg with ai
        proc fft_set_real with c, k, ar
        proc fft_set_imag with c, k, neg_ai
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_div_pointwise" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, c as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    c[k] = a[k] / b[k] = a[k] * conj(b[k]) / |b[k]|^2.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    For each coefficient compute numer = a * conj(b), denom = |b|^2,
    then divide each numer part by denom.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    n complex divides ~= 6 mulsd + 1 addsd + 2 divsd per coefficient.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Division latency may depend on operand magnitude on some AMD parts.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let ar be proc fft_get_real with a, k
        Let ai be proc fft_get_imag with a, k
        Let br be proc fft_get_real with b, k
        Let bi be proc fft_get_imag with b, k
        Note: numer = (ar + ai*i)(br - bi*i) = (ar*br + ai*bi) + (ai*br - ar*bi)i
        Let m1 be proc FP.fp_mul with ar, br
        Let m2 be proc FP.fp_mul with ai, bi
        Let nr be proc FP.fp_add with m1, m2
        Let m3 be proc FP.fp_mul with ai, br
        Let m4 be proc FP.fp_mul with ar, bi
        Let ni be proc FP.fp_sub with m3, m4
        Let m5 be proc FP.fp_mul with br, br
        Let m6 be proc FP.fp_mul with bi, bi
        Let denom be proc FP.fp_add with m5, m6
        Let div_r be proc FP.fp_div with nr, denom
        Let div_i be proc FP.fp_div with ni, denom
        proc fft_set_real with c, k, div_r
        proc fft_set_imag with c, k, div_i
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
Conversion between integer polynomial form and FFT input form
==============================================================================
The Falcon keygen produces small-integer polynomials f, g with coefficients
in roughly [-127, 127]. The signing path's c polynomial has coefficients in
[0, q-1]. Both must be lifted into the complex FFT input format.
:End Note

Process called "fft_load_from_int16_signed" takes int_poly as Integer, fft_buf as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Loads n int16 (signed) values from int_poly into the real parts of
    fft_buf with zero imaginary parts.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    For each k, reads int16 from int_poly[k*2], converts to Float via
    fp_from_int, writes to fft_buf as (real, 0).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    n cvtsi2sd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    int_poly may be SECRET; loop count public.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let off be k multiplied by 2
        Let v_raw be Memory.memory_get_int16(int_poly, off)
        Note: memory_get_int16 returns sign-extended already.
        Let v_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with v_raw
        proc fft_set_real with fft_buf, k, v_f
        Let zero_v be proc FP.fp_zero
        proc fft_set_imag with fft_buf, k, zero_v
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_load_from_int16_modq" takes int_poly as Integer, fft_buf as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Loads n int16 values interpreted as elements of Z/(q=12289) and centers
    them in [-q/2, q/2] before lifting to Float.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    For each k, reads int16; if value > q/2 subtract q; convert to Float.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    n loads + cvtsi2sd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Used in the Falcon hash-to-point lift; data is public per spec.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let q be 12289
    Let half_q be 6144
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let off be k multiplied by 2
        Let raw be Memory.memory_get_int16(int_poly, off)
        If raw is greater than half_q:
            Set raw to raw minus q
        End If
        Let v_f be proc FP.fp_from_int with raw
        proc fft_set_real with fft_buf, k, v_f
        Let zero_v be proc FP.fp_zero
        proc fft_set_imag with fft_buf, k, zero_v
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_extract_real_round" takes fft_buf as Integer, int_poly as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    For each coefficient writes round-to-nearest-even of the real part as
    an int16 to int_poly.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    fp_to_int_round then sign-truncated 16-bit store.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    n cvtsd2si.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Used in the inverse-FFT extraction; data may be SECRET in the keygen
    path (output of NTRUSolve descent levels).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let v_f be proc fft_get_real with fft_buf, k
        Let v_int be proc FP.fp_to_int_round with v_f
        Let off be k multiplied by 2
        Memory.memory_set_int16(int_poly, off, v_int)
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fft_squared_norm" takes fft_buf as Integer, n as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Compute the squared L2 norm of an FFT-domain polynomial.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Sum over k of |buf[k]|^2 = sum over k of (real_k^2 + imag_k^2).
    For an FFT-form polynomial this corresponds to n times the coefficient
    domain squared norm (Parseval's identity for the cyclotomic transform).
    Caller can divide by n if coefficient-domain norm is required.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    2n mulsd + 2n addsd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    The accumulated value depends on potentially SECRET coefficient
    magnitudes but addsd is constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let acc be proc FP.fp_zero
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than n:
        Let r be proc fft_get_real with fft_buf, k
        Let i_v be proc fft_get_imag with fft_buf, k
        Let r2 be proc FP.fp_mul with r, r
        Let i2 be proc FP.fp_mul with i_v, i_v
        Set acc to proc FP.fp_add with acc, r2
        Set acc to proc FP.fp_add with acc, i2
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return acc
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
Polynomial multiplication in Z[X]/(X^n+1) via FFT round-trip
==============================================================================
Two int16-array inputs, one int16-array output. The output is rounded to
nearest integer.
:End Note

Process called "fft_poly_multiply_int_via_fft" takes arena as Integer, a_int as Integer, b_int as Integer, c_int as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Compute c = a * b in Z[X]/(X^n+1) using the FFT round-trip.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Allocate two scratch buffers of 16*n bytes each.
    2. Load a, b into the buffers (real coefs, zero imag).
    3. fft_forward both.
    4. Pointwise multiply into buf_a.
    5. fft_inverse the product.
    6. fft_extract_real_round into c_int.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three FFTs + one pointwise mul = O(n log n).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Inputs may be SECRET (Falcon keygen secret polynomials).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let bytes be n multiplied by 16
    Let buf_a be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, bytes)
    Let buf_b be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, bytes)
    proc fft_load_from_int16_signed with a_int, buf_a, n
    proc fft_load_from_int16_signed with b_int, buf_b, n
    proc fft_forward with arena, buf_a, n
    proc fft_forward with arena, buf_b, n
    proc fft_mul_pointwise with buf_a, buf_b, buf_a, n
    proc fft_inverse with arena, buf_a, n
    proc fft_extract_real_round with buf_a, c_int, n
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
==============================================================================
END falcon_fft
==============================================================================
:End Note
